    <annotation>
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>4. Anic Martij historia regia.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Ancus Marcius"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>4. The royal history of Ancus Martius.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Ancus mixtae dispositionis, mediiq[ue] inter pacem, et bellum ingenij: vt pla[e]riq[ue] hodierni Reges.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Ancus Marcius"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Ancus had a mixed character, his nature holding the middle between war and peace, just like most Kings today.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Hacten&ugrave;s Tulli Historia.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Tullus Hostilius"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" type="curved" text="historia"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>So far the history of Tullus.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>} perit&egrave; compositus Rex. Foelicissimus procedendi modus, qui Tempori maxime opportunus.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>A skilfully restrained king. The most productive policy, which was especially suitable for this time.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Indicendi belli ritus.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The procedure for declaring war.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>dies 33. Iusti belli denunciatio: etiam hodierno Iure legitima. s[upr]a, in regno Tulli. i[nfr]a, 275 directa belli denunciatio. 
                        Vbi seria[e] Legationes, et pragmatica[e], de maximo mundi Bello.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Tullus Hostilius"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Thirty-three days: a declaration of a just war, still legitimate in today’s law. See above during Tullus’ reign. 
                For a straightforward declaration of war, see below p. 275, where there are serious and pragmatic embassies, concerning the greatest war in the world.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Huc litera[e] Martis: represalia: commissiones classica[e]: vis vi repulsa iure gentium.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>On this point: letters of war, reprisals, the soundings of war trumpets; violence warded off with violence according to the law of nations.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>( Huc doctor Gentilis de iure Belli: post Sigonium, Rosinum, Bellaium, et quosdam Iurisconsultos de Legibus Militaribus.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Alberico Gentili"/>
                    <person name="Carlo Sigonio"/>
                    <person name="Johannes Rosinus"/>
                    <person name="Guillaume du Bellay"/>
                    <book title="De iure belli libri tres"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>On this point see Dr Gentili De iure Belli, then Sigonius, Rosinus, Bellaius and a few legal scholars of military laws.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
